# Arduino Hardware Chatbot – Hardware Requirements

This document outlines the **hardware components, wiring details, and physical setup** required for the Arduino-based Hardware Chatbot project.

---

## 1. Core Components

| Component | Quantity | Purpose |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| **Arduino Board** (Uno / Mega / ESP32) | 1 | Main microcontroller to control hardware |
| **USB Cable** | 1 | Power supply & code upload |
| **Microphone Module** (e.g., MAX9814) | 1 | Captures voice input |
| **Speaker / Buzzer** | 1 | Audio output / notifications |
| **Servo Motor** (e.g., SG90) | 1–2 | For movement / gestures |
| **Ultrasonic Sensor** (HC-SR04) | 1 | Distance detection |
| **LEDs** (RGB or single color) | 2–3 | Visual response indicators |
| **Resistors** (220Ω, 1kΩ) | As needed | Current control for LEDs/sensors |
| **Breadboard** | 1 | Prototyping circuit |
| **Jumper Wires** (Male-Male, Male-Female) | 20+ | Connections between components |

---

## 2. Optional Components

| Component | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| **ESP8266/ESP32** | For WiFi-enabled chatbot |
| **OLED/LCD Display (16x2 or 20x4)** | Show text/chat responses |
| **Relay Module** | Control high-voltage devices |
| **Camera Module** | For vision-based chatbot features |

---

## 3. Wiring Guidelines

- **Power Supply:** Use Arduino’s 5V pin for most sensors, 3.3V for ESP-based boards.
- **Ground Connections:** Always connect all components to common GND.
- **Signal Pins:**
  - Servo Motor → Digital pins (e.g., D9)
  - Ultrasonic Sensor → Trigger & Echo pins (e.g., D7, D8)
  - Microphone → Analog pin (e.g., A0)
  - LEDs → Digital pins (e.g., D3, D4, D5)
- **Serial Communication:** Connect via USB for Python integration.

---

## 4. Estimated Cost

| Item | Approx. Price (INR) |
|------|--------------------|
| Arduino Uno | ₹500–₹700 |
| Microphone Module | ₹200–₹300 |
| Servo Motor | ₹150–₹250 each |
| Ultrasonic Sensor | ₹120–₹180 |
| Breadboard + Jumper Wires | ₹200–₹300 |
| Misc. Components | ₹100–₹200 |

---

## 5. Assembly Tips

- Use a **breadboard** for initial prototyping before soldering.
- Keep wires short to reduce signal interference.
- Label wires or use color codes for easy debugging.
- If using motors or servos, provide **external power** to avoid Arduino resets.
- For permanent setup, design a PCB or use a project box.

---

**Note:** The exact hardware list may vary depending on the complexity of your chatbot (voice-only, voice + movement, or AI + IoT integration).
